1308, November 27.

To this Court came Herve' le Taverner, of Nottingham, and Cecily his wife, and acknowledged that they had given to Richard de Greimst0n‚ of the same, four shillings of annual rent, with appur- tenances‚ issuing from all that tenement, with appurtenances and edifices there constructed, which lies upon Snowedon in the French Borough of the town of Nottingham, between the messuage formerly belonging to Richard le wast, on the western side, and a lane which leads from the Friars Minor to the mills of the Castle of Nottingham, on the south side: to be received yearly by our hands or by the hands of whosoever holds the aforesaid tenement, to wit, two shillings at the feast of the Invention of the Holy Cross, and two shillings at the feast of Saint Martin in Winter: to have and to hold to the aforesaid Richard, his heirs or assigns, for ever, as appears in the charter of feoffment. 1252, ro. 2d.
